{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20181016052423|864268074","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Joyce_Beatty","to":"Joyce Beatty"}],"pages":{"881669":{"pageid":881669,"ns":0,"title":"Joyce Beatty","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-10-26T11:14:21Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Joyce Beatty\n|image        = Joyce Beatty congressional portrait 114th Congress.jpg\n|state        = [[Ohio]]\n|district     = {{ushr|OH|3|3rd}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2013\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Mike Turner]]\n|successor    = \n|state_house1 = Ohio\n|district1    = 27th\n|term_start1  = May 31, 1999\n|term_end1    = December 31, 2008\n|predecessor1 = [[Otto Beatty Jr.]]\n|successor1   = [[W. Carlton Weddington]]\n|birth_name   = Joyce Birdsong Hannah\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1950|03|12}}\n|birth_place  = [[Dayton, Ohio]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = [[Otto Beatty Jr.]]\n|education    = [[Central State University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Wright State University]] ([[Master of Science|MS]])<br>[[University of Cincinnati]]\n|website      = {{url|beatty.house.gov|House website}}\n|residence    = [[Columbus, Ohio]]\n}}\n'''Joyce Birdson Beatty''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|e\u026a|t|i}} (n\u00e9e '''Hannah'''; born March 12, 1950) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] for [[Ohio's 3rd congressional district]] since 2013. Previously, she was the Senior Vice-President for Outreach and Engagement at [[Ohio State University]]. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], Beatty was a member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]] from 1999 to 2008, representing the 27th House District; in the Ohio House of Representatives, she served for a time as [[Minority Leader]]. Her husband is [[Otto Beatty Jr.]], who is also a former Ohio State Representative.\n\nIn 2012, she ran for the newly redrawn [[Ohio's 3rd congressional district]], based in the City of [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]], and won the Democratic primary by defeating former U.S. Congresswoman [[Mary Jo Kilroy]].<ref name=\"politico1\">[http://www.politico.com/2012-election/map/#/House/2012/Primary/OH 2012 Election Results Map by State \u2013 Live Voting Updates \u2013 POLITICO.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Beatty went on to win the [[general election]] against Chris Long.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ex-Ohio Rep. Beatty wins new US House district|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Ex-Ohio-Rep-Beatty-wins-new-US-House-district-4015659.php|work=sfgate.com|accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, family, education, and early political career==\nBeatty was born in Dayton, Ohio. She has a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in speech from [[Central State University]], an [[Master of Science|M.S.]] in [[counseling psychology]] from [[Wright State University]] in 1975<ref name=\"Wright State\">{{citation|url=https://corescholar.libraries.wright.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://www.google.com/&httpsredir=1&article=1068&context=alumnews|title=Making a career of beginnings|work=AlumNews|publisher=Wright State University Alumni Association|page=13|date=Spring 1991|volume=12|issue=4}}</ref> and has studied at the doctoral level at the [[University of Cincinnati]]. Beatty served as the Montgomery County Health and Human Services Director responsible for administering the county's health levy and area public nursing homes, including Stillwater Nursing Home. In 2003, she received an [[honorary doctorate]] from the [[Ohio Dominican University]]. Beatty served as a delegate for [[John Kerry]] on the [[Ohio]] delegation to the [[2004 Democratic National Convention]] in [[Boston]].<ref name=\"Bio\">{{cite web |url=https://beatty.house.gov/about/full-biography |title=Congresswoman Joyce Beatty |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= |publisher=United States House of Representatives |access-date=13 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nBeatty is married to attorney and former State Representative [[Otto Beatty Jr.]]  She has been a national spokesperson for the [[American Heart Association]]. She served on the [[American Heart Association|Columbus American Heart Association Board]], Ohio Democratic Committee, Women's Fund, [[NAACP]], and [[Delta Sigma Theta]] sorority. In addition, she was a legislative chair of The Links and was a chairwoman of the Columbus Urban League Board. She won the 2002 YWCA Woman of Achievement Award, the Ohio Health Speaking of Women Health Award, NAACP Freedom Award, Woman of Courage Award, and the Urban League Leadership Recognition Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ohioladiesgallery.org/PublicOfficial.aspx?personId=83540 |title=Ohio Ladies Gallery |publisher=Ohio Ladies Gallery |date= |accessdate=2012-03-15}}</ref>\n\n==Ohio House of Representatives (1999\u20132009)==\n\n===Elections===\nIn 1999, longtime State Representative [[Otto Beatty Jr.]] of Ohio's 21st House District decided to resign early to begin an opportunity in the private sector.  His wife, Joyce Beatty, was appointed to his seat.  She won a full term in 2000 with 82% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=196394 |title=OH State House 21 Race \u2013 Nov 07, 2000 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sos.state.oh.us/SOS/elections/electResultsMain/2000ElectionsResults/OHHouseReps11072000.aspx | title=2000 general election results | accessdate=September 13, 2011 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110627172935/http://www.sos.state.oh.us/SOS/elections/electResultsMain/2000ElectionsResults/OHHouseReps11072000.aspx | archivedate=June 27, 2011 | df= }}</ref> After redistricting, she decided to run in the newly redrawn Ohio's 27th House District and won re-election to a second term in 2002 with 82% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=49128 |title=OH State House 27 Race \u2013 Nov 05, 2002 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-03-15}}</ref> In 2004, she won re-election to a third term unopposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=71909 |title=OH State House 27 Race \u2013 Nov 02, 2004 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-03-15}}</ref> In 2006, she won re-election to a fourth term with 87% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=304026 |title=OH State House 27 Race \u2013 Nov 07, 2006 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-03-15}}</ref> [[Term limits]] kept Beatty from seeking another term in 2008, but her leadership helped Democrats to obtain the majority in the [[128th Ohio General Assembly]].\n\n===Tenure===\nAfter [[Chris Redfern]] left to become chairman of the [[Ohio Democratic Party]], Beatty was named Minority Leader.  She served in that capacity for the entire [[Ohio 127th General Assembly]]. She was the first female Democratic House Leader in Ohio history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beattyforcongress.com/about |title=Beatty For Congress |publisher=Beatty For Congress |date=2009-03-25 |accessdate=2012-03-15}}</ref>\n\n==Ohio State University (2008\u20132012)==\nFollowing her time in the House, she became Senior Vice-President for Outreach and Engagement at [[Ohio State University]].\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio, 2012#District 3}}\nOn March 6, 2012, Beatty defeated former Congresswoman [[Mary Jo Kilroy]], Columbus city councilwoman Priscilla Tyson, and state representative [[Ted Celeste]] 38%\u201335%-15%-12% to win the Ohio 3rd Congressional District Democratic Primary.<ref name=\"politico1\"/> Beatty received early support from the Ohio Legislative Black Caucus, [[List of mayors of Columbus, Ohio|Columbus Mayor]] [[Michael B. Coleman]], and various other Central Ohio political figures including Rep. [[Tracy Maxwell Heard]] and former Rep. [[W. Carlton Weddington]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://beattyforcongress.com/endorsements |title=Beatty For Congress |publisher=Beatty For Congress |date=2009-03-25 |accessdate=2012-03-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306142309/http://beattyforcongress.com/endorsements |archivedate=2012-03-06 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]'''\n**[[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Housing and Insurance|Subcommittee on Housing and Insurance]]\n**[[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[Congressional Black Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://cbc.house.gov/membership/|format=|publisher=Congressional Black Caucus|date=|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Compensation===\nOn June 21, 2013, the ''[[National Journal]]'' published an article, \"Nearly One in Five Members of Congress Gets Paid Twice\". It was reported that Beatty's state pension of $253,323 is the highest, and combined with her congressional salary is greater than President Obama's total government compensation.<ref>[http://www.nationaljournal.com/magazine/nearly-one-in-five-members-of-congress-gets-paid-twice-20130627 Nearly One in Five Members of Congress Gets Paid Twice \u2013 NationalJournal.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of African-American United States Representatives]]\n*[[Women in the United States House of Representatives]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://beatty.house.gov/ Congresswoman Joyce Beatty] official U.S. House site\n*[http://beattyforcongress.com/ Joyce Beatty for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Ohio/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Joyce_Beatty_%5BD-03%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=B001281 | votesmart=2427 | fec=H2OH03125 | congress=joyce-beatty/2153 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n|state= Ohio\n|district= 3\n| before=[[Mike Turner]]\n| years=2013\u2013Present\n| after=Incumbent}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Andy Barr (U.S. politician)|Andy Barr]]<br>R-[[Kentucky]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=248th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ami Bera]]<br>D-[[California]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{OH-FedRep}}\n{{OhioRepresentatives03}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 113th\u2013115th [[United States Congress]]es |state=[[United States congressional delegations from Ohio|Ohio]]}}\n{{USCongRep/OH/113}}\n{{USCongRep/OH/114}}\n{{USCongRep/OH/115}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beatty, Joyce}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:African-American members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:African-American women in politics]]\n[[Category:Central State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Ohio House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Ohio Democrats]]\n[[Category:Women state legislators in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Female members of the U